properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow tonight. A low pressure system over southern BC will continue to spread snow over the region tonight. As well, an arctic front has arrived with strong gusty winds resulting in dropping temperatures. The combination of falling snow with very strong winds will result in blowing snow and poor visibility. For the southwest interior the worst conditions are expected this evening. Visibility will improve through the night as snow tapers off and winds ease. For Yoho Park, Kootenay Park, and Elk Valley, the winds will ease and visibility will improve by Monday morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: The low pressure system continues its trek across the south coast this afternoon. In the wake of the low, northeast outflow winds will collide with northwest winds from the Strait of Georgia. Where they meet, a localised band of heavy snow will develop and push through Metro Vancouver this evening for further localised accumulations of 5 cm. Higher elevations of West Vancouver, North Vancouver and Coquitlam will continue to see some snow today with a further 5 cm possible. Vancouver, Burnaby and New Westminster will see rain mixed with wet snow. Precipitation type will depend on proximity to the water, elevation, precipitation intensity and wind direction. Richmond, Delta, Tsawwassen and Ladner will continue to see rain today as the southerly winds have been keeping temperatures above freezing. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A multi-day episode of very cold wind chills is expected. Bitterly cold air becoming entrenched in western Saskatchewan... A ridge of high pressure is bringing very cold air from Alaska into the western Prairies. Wind chill values have been dropping throughout the day, and will reach the -40 mark late this afternoon or tonight. The cold will continue to deepen and push eastward as the week progresses. Temperatures are not expected to climb above -20 for at least the next week. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Coldest Windchills: -45. Location: Labrador City and vicinity. Time span: overnight Monday night. Remarks: Wind chills are expected to approach but not reach -45 tonight as cloud cover is expected to keep temperatures relatively warm.
